{"action": "input", "code": "def find_patterns(sub1: np.ndarray, back_1: int, sub2: np.ndarray, back_2: int) -> Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Finds the patterns in sub1 and sub2.\n\n    Args:\n    sub1: A numpy array representing the first sub-grid.\n    back_1: An integer representing the most common color in sub1.\n    sub2: A numpy array representing the second sub-grid.\n    back_2: An integer representing the most common color in sub2.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of two tuples of two integers each representing the coordinates of the top-left pixel of the pattern in sub1 and sub2, respectively.\n    \"\"\"\n    patterns = []\n    for sub in [sub1, sub2]:\n        for i in range(1, sub.shape[0] - 1):\n            for j in range(1, sub.shape[1] - 1):\n                if sub[i, j] != back_1 and sub[i - 1:i + 2, j - 1:j + 2].max() != sub[i, j] and (sub[i - 1:i + 2, j - 1:j + 2].min() != sub[i, j]):\n                    patterns.append((i - 1, j - 1))\n    return (patterns[0], patterns[1])\ndef split_grid(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[np.ndarray, np.ndarray]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Splits the input grid along the horizontal or vertical direction, such that one of the two resulting grids has 4 colors\n    while the other has 3 colors.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of two numpy arrays representing the two resulting grids.\n    \"\"\"\n    rows, cols = input_grid.shape\n    if rows == 3:\n        sub1 = input_grid[:, :cols // 2]\n        sub2 = input_grid[:, cols // 2:]\n    else:\n        sub1 = input_grid[:rows // 2, :]\n        sub2 = input_grid[rows // 2:, :]\n    if len(np.unique(sub1)) == 4:\n        return (sub1, sub2)\n    else:\n        return (sub2, sub1)\ndef copy_pattern(sub1: np.ndarray, back_1: int, p1: Tuple[int, int], sub2: np.ndarray, back_2: int, p2: Tuple[int, int], match: bool) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Copies the pattern in sub1 to sub2 in the matched position.\n\n    Args:\n    sub1: A numpy array representing the first sub-grid.\n    back_1: An integer representing the most common color in sub1.\n    p1: A tuple of two integers representing the coordinates of the top-left pixel of the pattern in sub1.\n    sub2: A numpy array representing the second sub-grid.\n    back_2: An integer representing the most common color in sub2.\n    p2: A tuple of two integers representing the coordinates of the top-left pixel of the pattern in sub2.\n    match: A boolean value indicating whether the patterns in sub1 and sub2 match.\n\n    Returns:\n    A numpy array representing the output grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    if not match:\n        return sub2\n    dx, dy = np.array(p2) - np.array(p1)\n    rows, cols = sub1.shape\n    out = sub2.copy()\n    for i in range(rows):\n        for j in range(cols):\n            if sub1[i, j] != back_1:\n                out[i + dx, j + dy] = sub1[i, j]\n    return out\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    sub1, sub2 = split_grid(input_grid)\n    back_1, back_2 = find_most_color(sub1, sub2)\n    p1, p2 = find_patterns(sub1, back_1, sub2, back_2)\n    match = match_patterns(sub1, back_1, p1, sub2, back_2, p2)\n    out = copy_pattern(sub1, back_1, p1, sub2, back_2, p2, match)\n    return out\ndef find_most_color(sub1: np.ndarray, sub2: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Finds the most common color in sub1 and sub2.\n\n    Args:\n    sub1: A numpy array representing the first sub-grid.\n    sub2: A numpy array representing the second sub-grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of two integers representing the most common color in sub1 and sub2, respectively.\n    \"\"\"\n    color_counts = np.bincount(np.concatenate((sub1.flatten(), sub2.flatten())))\n    return (np.argmax(color_counts), np.argsort(color_counts)[-2])\ndef match_patterns(sub1: np.ndarray, back_1: int, p1: Tuple[int, int], sub2: np.ndarray, back_2: int, p2: Tuple[int, int]) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"\n    Matches the patterns in sub1 and sub2.\n\n    Args:\n    sub1: A numpy array representing the first sub-grid.\n    back_1: An integer representing the most common color in sub1.\n    p1: A tuple of two integers representing the coordinates of the top-left pixel of the pattern in sub1.\n    sub2: A numpy array representing the second sub-grid.\n    back_2: An integer representing the most common color in sub2.\n    p2: A tuple of two integers representing the coordinates of the top-left pixel of the pattern in sub2.\n\n    Returns:\n    A boolean value indicating whether the patterns in sub1 and sub2 match.\n    \"\"\"\n    for color in set(sub1.flatten()) - {back_1}:\n        if np.sum(sub1 == color) != np.sum(sub2 == color):\n            return False\n        if not np.all(np.where(sub1 == color) - np.array(p1) == np.where(sub2 == color) - np.array(p2)):\n            return False\n    return True", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    sub1, sub2 = `split the input_grid along the horizontal or vertical direction, the 1 of 2 grids should have 4 color when the other has 3`(input_grid)\n    back_1, back_2 = `find the most color in sub1 and sub2`(sub1, sub2)\n    p1, p2 = `a pattern is a 3x3 area which some not back color pixel in it and pixels around is not in that color, find patterns in sub1 and sub2`(sub1, back_1, sub2, back_2)\n    match = `match the pattern in p1 and p2, if for any color that is not back color, for 2 patterns, the number of pixels in the color and the relative position between pixels in the color is same, recognize patterns are matched`(sub1, back_1, p1, sub2, back_2, p2)\n    out = `copy the pattern in the sub which has 4 colors to the other sub in the matched position`(sub1, back_1, p1, sub2, back_2, p2, match)\n    return out", "gpt_code": "def find_patterns(sub1: np.ndarray, back_1: int, sub2: np.ndarray, back_2: int) -> Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Finds the patterns in sub1 and sub2.\n\n    Args:\n    sub1: A numpy array representing the first sub-grid.\n    back_1: An integer representing the most common color in sub1.\n    sub2: A numpy array representing the second sub-grid.\n    back_2: An integer representing the most common color in sub2.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of two tuples of two integers each representing the coordinates of the top-left pixel of the pattern in sub1 and sub2, respectively.\n    \"\"\"\n    patterns = []\n    for sub in [sub1, sub2]:\n        for i in range(1, sub.shape[0] - 1):\n            for j in range(1, sub.shape[1] - 1):\n                if sub[i, j] != back_1 and sub[i - 1:i + 2, j - 1:j + 2].max() != sub[i, j] and (sub[i - 1:i + 2, j - 1:j + 2].min() != sub[i, j]):\n                    patterns.append((i - 1, j - 1))\n    return (patterns[0], patterns[1])\ndef split_grid(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[np.ndarray, np.ndarray]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Splits the input grid along the horizontal or vertical direction, such that one of the two resulting grids has 4 colors\n    while the other has 3 colors.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of two numpy arrays representing the two resulting grids.\n    \"\"\"\n    rows, cols = input_grid.shape\n    if rows == 3:\n        sub1 = input_grid[:, :cols // 2]\n        sub2 = input_grid[:, cols // 2:]\n    else:\n        sub1 = input_grid[:rows // 2, :]\n        sub2 = input_grid[rows // 2:, :]\n    if len(np.unique(sub1)) == 4:\n        return (sub1, sub2)\n    else:\n        return (sub2, sub1)\ndef copy_pattern(sub1: np.ndarray, back_1: int, p1: Tuple[int, int], sub2: np.ndarray, back_2: int, p2: Tuple[int, int], match: bool) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Copies the pattern in sub1 to sub2 in the matched position.\n\n    Args:\n    sub1: A numpy array representing the first sub-grid.\n    back_1: An integer representing the most common color in sub1.\n    p1: A tuple of two integers representing the coordinates of the top-left pixel of the pattern in sub1.\n    sub2: A numpy array representing the second sub-grid.\n    back_2: An integer representing the most common color in sub2.\n    p2: A tuple of two integers representing the coordinates of the top-left pixel of the pattern in sub2.\n    match: A boolean value indicating whether the patterns in sub1 and sub2 match.\n\n    Returns:\n    A numpy array representing the output grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    if not match:\n        return sub2\n    dx, dy = np.array(p2) - np.array(p1)\n    rows, cols = sub1.shape\n    out = sub2.copy()\n    for i in range(rows):\n        for j in range(cols):\n            if sub1[i, j] != back_1:\n                out[i + dx, j + dy] = sub1[i, j]\n    return out\ndef find_most_color(sub1: np.ndarray, sub2: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Finds the most common color in sub1 and sub2.\n\n    Args:\n    sub1: A numpy array representing the first sub-grid.\n    sub2: A numpy array representing the second sub-grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of two integers representing the most common color in sub1 and sub2, respectively.\n    \"\"\"\n    color_counts = np.bincount(np.concatenate((sub1.flatten(), sub2.flatten())))\n    return (np.argmax(color_counts), np.argsort(color_counts)[-2])\ndef match_patterns(sub1: np.ndarray, back_1: int, p1: Tuple[int, int], sub2: np.ndarray, back_2: int, p2: Tuple[int, int]) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"\n    Matches the patterns in sub1 and sub2.\n\n    Args:\n    sub1: A numpy array representing the first sub-grid.\n    back_1: An integer representing the most common color in sub1.\n    p1: A tuple of two integers representing the coordinates of the top-left pixel of the pattern in sub1.\n    sub2: A numpy array representing the second sub-grid.\n    back_2: An integer representing the most common color in sub2.\n    p2: A tuple of two integers representing the coordinates of the top-left pixel of the pattern in sub2.\n\n    Returns:\n    A boolean value indicatin